## Overview

Today I learned how to recover HTTP objects from captured network traffic using Wireshark. This technique allows Security Analysts and Digital Forensics Investigators to identify and recover files transferred over unencrypted HTTP connections.

---

## Objectives

- Understand how HTTP transfers files.
- Learn why HTTP traffic can be reconstructed.
- Export HTTP objects from a packet capture.
- Identify different file types transferred over HTTP.
- Understand the importance of HTTPS in protecting transmitted data.

---

## Tools Used

- Kali Linux
- Wireshark
- Mozilla Firefox
- neverssl.com (HTTP website)

---

## Practical Activities

### 1. Captured HTTP Traffic

- Started packet capture on the **wlan0** interface.
- Visited **http://neverssl.com** using Firefox.
- Generated HTTP traffic.
- Stopped the packet capture.

---

### 2. Filtered HTTP Packets

Applied the following Wireshark display filter:

```
http
```

This displayed all HTTP requests and responses exchanged between my computer and the web server.

---

### 3. Exported HTTP Objects

Opened:

```
File
    └── Export Objects
            └── HTTP
```

Recovered the following HTTP objects:

| Filename | Content Type | Size |
|----------|--------------|------|
| / | text/html | 3,961 Bytes |
| online | text/html | 300 Bytes |
| online | text/html | 2,238 Bytes |
| favicon.ico | image/vnd.microsoft.icon | 124 Bytes |

---

## What I Learned

- HTTP sends data in plain text.
- Wireshark can reconstruct files transferred over HTTP.
- HTML pages and website resources can be recovered from packet captures.
- The website favicon is transferred as a separate object.
- HTTPS traffic cannot normally be reconstructed because it is encrypted using TLS.

---

## Why This Matters

Recovering HTTP objects is an important technique in Digital Forensics and Incident Response. During an investigation, analysts may recover:

- HTML pages
- Images
- JavaScript files
- CSS files
- PDF documents
- Downloaded files
- Malware delivered over HTTP

This helps investigators understand what users accessed or downloaded during an incident.

